			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
			
			
			
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041052a2b5bb012d4490764903985&amp;subject_id=0024004102975ad83011b2b83251c0c35">Students Honored for Academics, Leadership and Service</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041052a2b5bb012d44907649037fd&amp;subject_id=0024004102975ad83011b2b83251c0c35">Emeritus Awards: Lifetimes of Distinction</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041052a2b5bb012d449076490380a&amp;subject_id=0024004102975ad83011b2b83251c0c35">Faculty Honored for Excellence at Founders' Day Ceremony</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>A chemist who has earned more than $5 million in research funding and a professor known for mentoring students as they establish their research careers have won UCF&rsquo;s most prestigious faculty award.</p>
<p><strong>Kevin Belfield</strong> and <strong>Ranganathan Kumar</strong> received their Pegasus Professor awards today during the annual Founders&rsquo; Day ceremony. The award recognizes extraordinary contributions to the UCF community through teaching, research and service.</p>
<p>Since 2000, only 23 UCF professors have received the award.</p>
<p>As Pegasus Professors, Belfield and Kumar each received a statue of the UCF Pegasus, a gold Pegasus Professor medallion and a check for $5,000.</p>
<p><strong>Kevin Belfield</strong> has taught at UCF since 1998. As chair of the Chemistry Department for the past six years, he has led efforts to expand the department&rsquo;s faculty and the number of bachelor&rsquo;s degrees awarded. Belfield also led the development of the Chemistry Ph.D. program, which has graduated more than 20 doctoral students since 2003.</p>
<p>Belfield has published more than 160 papers, given more than 200 research presentations and reviewed 25 scientific journals. He also has been awarded seven U.S. patents. He has brought in more than $5 million in research funding, earning him a place in the Millionaire&rsquo;s Club, a special tradition at UCF recognizing faculty members who have garnered more than $1 million in research grants in a given year.</p>
<p>He has also been a shining example of interdisciplinary service, participating in the Faculty Senate, UCF Research Council and committees for numerous colleges, including Medicine and Optics and Photonics.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dr. Belfield is truly a unique individual at UCF,&rdquo; said Peter Panousis, dean of the College of Sciences.&nbsp; &ldquo;He is a superb, award-winning teacher, recognized as a world-class scholar who has demonstrated outstanding capability as a university administrator.&rdquo;</p>
<p><strong>Ranganathan Kumar</strong> has been a professor of Mechanical, Materials and Aerospace Engineering since joining the university in 2003, and he also served as the department&rsquo;s chair for several years.</p>
<p>Kumar has excelled in his own work in nanofluids and microfluids heat transfer, and he has promoted opportunity by encouraging the work of his students and assisting faculty members with writing and research. His own contributions to the field have brought in $2.4 million in research funding, and his work has appeared in 140 articles, 60 scientific journals and 52 conference papers.</p>
<p>Under his leadership, his department&rsquo;s research funding has more than doubled, and five assistant professors have received prestigious CAREER awards, which are presented by the National Science Foundation to faculty members near the beginning of their careers. He&rsquo;s also served as principal investigator for two multi-year NSF grants that introduced students and teachers to the practice of research.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Dr. Kumar constantly exhibits exceptional abilities and foresight to pull together active researchers to respond to research opportunities while simultaneously concentrating on the quality of undergraduate education and outreach,&rdquo; said Suhada Jayasuriya, a distinguished professor and MMAE chair.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </strong>The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 2nd largest in the nation with more than 56,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
